"The dimmed lights of the Snug Harbor Cultural Center glimmered like scattered sapphires against the walls of peeling, vintage art deco décor. The hum of conversation, a low and steady tide, flowed through the main hall where folding chairs and clusters of folding tables were arranged in uneven, improvisational groups. Above, a flickering neon sign cast a warm, hazy halo over the linoleum floor, the air carrying the faintest trace of old perfume and spilled beer.\n\nOutside the stage curtain, a makeshift sign in faded gold script announced the evening’s karaoke event—“Sing to Live, Laugh, Remember.” Laughter bounced from the audience as volunteers stepped forward, their voices tentative at first, then boldening with each line. Jackson lingered by the edge of the makeshift queue, uncertain but drawn to the promise of release that a crowd like this could offer, even in the hush before the first song began.\n\nA hand tapped his shoulder, startling him out of his reverie. He turned to find a stranger with close-cropped hair and eyes like storm-tossed gray water. “You going first?” she asked, her voice soft, almost shy despite the crowd. Jackson shrugged, trying to seem nonchalant. But inside, anticipation prickled along his neck like static electricity.\n\nHe followed her to the green-lit queue, watching the lights flicker with each passing minute. The scent of popcorn and something metallic—cleaner than the bar but sharp—wove through the humid summer air. He glanced at the small stage up ahead, its black edges reflecting the faces of a few brave souls on the cusp of performance.\n\nThe DJ’s laughter boomed over the PA as he announced the next song. A murmur rippled through the crowd; Jackson felt his pulse quicken, the familiar thrill of exposure raw and unguarded. His throat felt tight, almost closed from the anticipation of what was to come. He closed his eyes, willing himself to breathe with the music rather than against it.\n\nThen the house lights dimmed, and the 